# 8 Weeks: Whole-Bacterium Assays & Effector Functions — Maternal TdaP vs TT {#inf2-effectors}

At the **infant baseline visit (8 weeks, before primary vaccination)** this part tests
whether **maternal TdaP** shifts the infant's whole-bacterium responses and antibody effector
functions relative to **maternal TT** (referent). It covers two families:

- **Whole-bacterium assays** — `r paste(gsub("^WHOLE_", "", INFMON2_WHOLE_ASSAYS), collapse = ", ")`
  (serum bactericidal activity, whole-cell-binding IgG, and pertussis-toxin neutralization).
- **Effector functions** binding to individual antigens — **ADCD** (all six antigens
  `r paste(INFMON2_EFFECTOR_ANTIGENS$ADCD, collapse = ", ")`), and **ADCP** / **ADNP**
  (`r paste(INFMON2_EFFECTOR_ANTIGENS$ADCP, collapse = ", ")` only — no FHA or FIM assays).

Each feature is a **Wilcoxon rank-sum test of TdaP vs TT on log10 assay values — the same test
used in the response-bubble grid.** Multiplicity is handled by
**Benjamini–Hochberg within each assay class** (Whole / ADCD / ADCP / ADNP as separate families).
The forest plot additionally carries the point estimate + interval that natively pair with that
test: the **Hodges–Lehmann location shift and its Wilcoxon CI**, oriented **TdaP − TT**. With **TT
as the reference level**, this is the effect of TdaP relative to TT, so a positive value means
*higher with maternal TdaP*.

